Security Audit Guide - Complete Checklist for Web Applications
🎯 Purpose
Comprehensive security audit checklist covering API key protection, environment variables, database security (Supabase RLS & MongoDB), authentication, and deployment security.

🔐 1. Environment Variables & API Key Security
1.1 Environment Variable Best Practices
✅ Correct Setup
# .env.local (Next.js) or .env (Node.js)
# Database
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://..."
SUPABASE_URL="https://xxx.supabase.co"
SUPABASE_ANON_KEY="eyJhbGci..."

# API Keys (prefix determines client/server exposure)
NEXT_PUBLIC_STRIPE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY="pk_test_..."  # Client-side safe
STRIPE_SECRET_KEY="sk_test_..."                   # Server-side only
OPENAI_API_KEY="sk-..."                           # Server-side only

# Authentication
NEXTAUTH_SECRET="generated-secret-32-chars-minimum"
NEXTAUTH_URL="http://localhost:3000"

# Third-party Services
SENDGRID_API_KEY="SG...."
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET="..."

🔍 Audit Checklist - Environment Files
[ ] .env files in .gitignore - ALL .env files excluded from version control
[ ] .env.example exists - Template file with dummy values for team
[ ] No secrets in code - Zero hardcoded API keys in source files
[ ] Naming convention - Public keys prefixed (NEXT_PUBLIC_, VITE_, REACT_APP_)
[ ] Minimum key length - Secrets are 32+ characters
[ ] No .env in public folder - Environment files never in public/static directories
[ ] Key rotation schedule - API keys rotated every 90 days
❌ Common Violations to Flag
// CRITICAL VIOLATION - Hardcoded API Key
const apiKey = "sk_live_51Hp...";  // ❌ NEVER DO THIS

// CRITICAL VIOLATION - Key in client-side code
const stripe = Stripe("sk_test_...");  // ❌ Secret key exposed

// VIOLATION - Committing .env file
git add .env  // ❌ Never commit

// VIOLATION - API key in URL parameters
fetch(`https://api.service.com/data?key=${API_KEY}`)  // ❌ Exposed in logs

// CORRECT - Server-side only
// server-side file only
const apiKey = process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY;  // ✅ Safe

